Statistical Methods for Microbiome Analysis

Malu Calle, University of Vic - Central University of Catalonia

This tutorial is based on several phyloseq tutorials that are available at https://joey711.github.io/phyloseq/

1 Elements of a phyloseq object

Make a copy of default graphical settings:

default.par <- par()      
#par(default.par)   # recover default graphical settings

Load libraries phyloseq and vegan:

# BiocManager::install("phyloseq")
library(phyloseq)
#install.packages("vegan")
library(vegan)

Load microbiome dataset GlobalPatterns:

data(GlobalPatterns)

Information on dataset GlobalPatterns:

Define a new factor variable called human that indicates which samples corresponde to human samples (feces, skin and tongue):

human.samples<-c("Feces", "Skin", "Tongue")
sample_data(data)$human<-rep(0,26)
sample_data(data)$human[sample_data(data)$SampleType%in%human.samples]<-1
sample_data(data)$human<-factor(sample_data(data)$human,levels=c(0,1),labels=c("No","Yes"))

Define a new dataframe called metadata that includes variables X.SampleID, SampleType, Description and human:

metadata<-as.data.frame(data@sam_data[,c(1,6,7,8)])

2 Phyloseq accessors

2.1 nsamples(physeq)

Number of samples in phyloseq object data:

nsamples(data)
## [1] 26

2.2 ntaxa(physeq)

Number of taxa or species in phyloseq object data:

ntaxa(data)
## [1] 19216

2.3 sample_names

Names of the samples in phyloseq object data:

sample_names(data)[1:5]
## [1] "CL3"     "CC1"     "SV1"     "M31Fcsw" "M11Fcsw"

2.4 taxa_names

Names of taxa (OTUs, species) in phyloseq object data:

taxa_names(data)[1:5]
## [1] "549322" "522457" "951"    "244423" "586076"

Names of the taxonomic ranks in phyloseq object data:

rank_names(data)
## [1] "Kingdom" "Phylum"  "Class"   "Order"   "Family"  "Genus"   "Species"

hist(sample_sums(data), breaks=10)

boxplot(log(sample_sums(data))~metadata$SampleType)

3 Preprocessing

3.1 prune_taxa

Specification of condition for those taxa you want to keep.

Example: Keep only those taxa with at least 10 counts:

data<-prune_taxa(taxa_sums(data)>10, data)

Summary of total number of counts per taxa after taxa pruning:

summary(taxa_sums(data))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##      11      34     113    2339     498 2481214

3.2 prune_samples

Specification of condition for those samples you want to keep.

Example: Keep only those samples with at least 10 counts:

data<-prune_samples(sample_sums(data)>10, data)

3.3 rarefaction: rarefy_even_depth()

Resample an OTU table such that all samples have the same library size.

Example: Create a new phyloseq object called raredata with all samples having the same library size, equal to the minimum of total number of counts per sample, using a random seed equal to 123:

raredata<-rarefy_even_depth(data, sample.size = min(sample_sums(data)), rngseed = 123)
## `set.seed(123)` was used to initialize repeatable random subsampling.
## Please record this for your records so others can reproduce.
## Try `set.seed(123); .Random.seed` for the full vector
## ...
## 1067OTUs were removed because they are no longer 
## present in any sample after random subsampling
## ...

Number of OTUs removed after rarefaction:

ntaxa(data)-ntaxa(raredata)
## [1] 1067

3.4 transform_sample_counts

Transform counts in an otu_table, sample-by-sample:

Example: Create a new phyloseq object called propdata with relative abundances:

propdata<-transform_sample_counts(data, function(x) x/sum(x))

Check that the total count per sample of propdata is 1:

sample_sums(propdata)
##      CL3      CC1      SV1  M31Fcsw  M11Fcsw  M31Plmr  M11Plmr  F21Plmr 
##        1        1        1        1        1        1        1        1 
##  M31Tong  M11Tong LMEpi24M SLEpi20M   AQC1cm   AQC4cm   AQC7cm      NP2 
##        1        1        1        1        1        1        1        1 
##      NP3      NP5  TRRsed1  TRRsed2  TRRsed3     TS28     TS29    Even1 
##        1        1        1        1        1        1        1        1 
##    Even2    Even3 
##        1        1

3.5 tax_glom

Agglomerate taxa at some taxonomic level.

Example: Create a new phyloseq object called dataKingdom with abundance data at Kingdom level:

dataKingdom<-tax_glom(data, "Kingdom")

Elements of phyloseq object dataKingdom:

dataKingdom
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 2 taxa and 26 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 26 samples by 8 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 2 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 2 tips and 1 internal nodes ]

Though the dataKingdom" is aglommerated at Kingdom level, the taxa names remain at OTU level:

taxa_names(dataKingdom)
## [1] "250392" "549656"

Redifine taxa names with Kingdom levels:

taxa_names(dataKingdom)<-as.vector(dataKingdom@tax_table[,1])
taxa_names(dataKingdom)
## [1] "Archaea"  "Bacteria"

Example: Create a new phyloseq object called propdataKingdom with relative abundance data at Kingdom level:

propdataKingdom<-tax_glom(propdata, rank_names(data)[1])
propdataKingdom
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 2 taxa and 26 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 26 samples by 8 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 2 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 2 tips and 1 internal nodes ]

Example: Create a new phyloseq object called dataPhylum with abundance data at Phylum level:

dataPhylum<-tax_glom(data, rank_names(data)[2])
dataPhylum
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 60 taxa and 26 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 26 samples by 8 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 60 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 60 tips and 59 internal nodes ]

Example: Create a new phyloseq object called propdataPhylum with relative abundance data at Phylum level:

propdataPhylum<-tax_glom(propdata, rank_names(data)[2])
propdataPhylum
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 60 taxa and 26 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 26 samples by 8 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 60 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks ]
## phy_tree()    Phylogenetic Tree: [ 60 tips and 59 internal nodes ]

Redifine taxa names with Phylum levels:

taxa_names(propdataPhylum)<-tax_table(propdataPhylum)[,2]

3.6 merge_taxa

Merge a subset of the species into one taxa.

Example: Merge those taxa with total relative abundance smaller than 0.8 into a new taxa:

Number of taxa with with total relative abundance smaller than 0.8:

sum(taxa_sums(propdataPhylum)<0.8)
## [1] 55

Define a vector of indices called less_freq_taxa corresponding to those taxa with total relative abundance smaller than 0.8:

less_freq_taxa<-which(taxa_sums(propdataPhylum)<0.8)

Define a new phyloseq object called propdataPhylum2 with those taxa with total relative abundance smaller than 0.8 merged:

propdataPhylum2<-merge_taxa(propdataPhylum,less_freq_taxa)

OTU table of less frequent taxa merged:

5 Phylogenetic tree

Example: Phylogenetic tree for Phylum = Acidobacteria and abundances aglomerated at Class level:

dataClass<-tax_glom(data, "Class")

Consider the subset of taxa called d corresponding to Acidobacteria Phylum:

d<-subset_taxa(dataClass, Phylum =="Acidobacteria")

Plot phylogenetic tree for d:

plot_tree(d,ladderize="left",size="abundance",color="human",label.tips="Class")

7 Beta diversity: between samples diversity

Estimate different beta diversity measures with function distance. Most common distances used are Bray-Curtis, Unifrac and weighted Unifrac.

Estimate Bray-Curtis distance:

BC.dist<-distance(data, method ="bray")

as.matrix(BC.dist)[1,2]
## [1] 0.5984077

Estimate Unifrac distance:

UF.dist<-distance(data, method = "unifrac")

Estimate weighted Unifrac distance:

wUF.dist<-distance(data, method = "wunifrac")

8 Ordination: Visualization of beta diversity

8.1 Principal Coordinates Analysis (PCoA) = Multidimensional Scaling (MDS)

Example: MDS for human samples

Define as data.human the subset of samples corresponding to human samples (feces, skin and tongue:

data.human<-subset_samples(data, human=="Yes")

Estimate Bray-Curtis distance among human samples:

BC.dist.human<-distance(data.human, method ="bray")

Perform MDS ordination of human samples with BC distance:

BC.MDS.human=ordinate(data.human,   "MDS",  distance    =   BC.dist.human)

Plot MDS ordination of human samples with BC distance:

plot_ordination(data.human, BC.MDS.human,   color="SampleType")

Estimate Unifrac distance among human samples:

UF.dist.human<-distance(data.human, method ="unifrac")

Perform MDS ordination of human samples with UF distance:

UF.MDS.human=ordinate(data.human,   "MDS",  distance    =   UF.dist.human)

Plot MDS ordination of human samples with UF distance:

plot_ordination(data.human, UF.MDS.human,   color="SampleType")

Estimate weighted Unifrac distance among human samples:

wUF.dist.human<-distance(data.human, method ="wunifrac")

Perform MDS ordination of human samples with wUF distance:

wUF.MDS.human=ordinate(data.human,  "MDS",  distance    =   wUF.dist.human)

Plot MDS ordination of human samples with wUF distance:

plot_ordination(data.human, wUF.MDS.human,  color="SampleType")
